Sure! Below is a simple Java program that generates and displays the multiplication table from 1 to 10:

```java
public class MultiplicationTable {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        // Loop through numbers 1 to 10 for the multiplication table
        for (int i = 1; i <= 10; i++) {
            System.out.println("Multiplication Table for " + i);
            System.out.println("----------------------------");
            // Loop through numbers 1 to 10 for each table
            for (int j = 1; j <= 10; j++) {
                System.out.println(i + " x " + j + " = " + (i * j));
            }
            System.out.println();
        }
    }
}
```

### How It Works:
- The outer loop (`for (int i = 1; i <= 10; i++)`) iterates through numbers from 1 to 10. This represents the multiplier for which the table is being created.
- The inner loop (`for (int j = 1; j <= 10; j++)`) iterates through numbers 1 to 10 for each multiplier. It calculates and prints the product of `i` and `j`.
- The `System.out.println()` statements are used to format the output neatly.

To run this program:
1. Copy the code into a file named `MultiplicationTable.java`.
2. Compile the program using `javac MultiplicationTable.java`.
3. Run the compiled program using `java MultiplicationTable`.

This will display the multiplication tables for numbers 1 through 10 in the console.
